Okay, I'll bite. I'm in a 'too tired to get my own shit written, but still want to contribute mood'...

Seriously, honestly, and truly, I mean it when I say this: Don't defeat yourself before you even start. If you look into our backlog, there have been some seriously shit writers. There are countless stories that struggle to hit 10k words, stories that lack any whiff of character development, stories with immersion breaking levels of breaking from the norm (think 'rando character X swims up to anon and asks to fuck... so they do') and stories that describe things so poorly as to allude to physical impossibility (think 'he licked her asshole while plowing her pussy' levels of bad.)

Save for some authors who've gone full autist over feedback, things generally go as follows: The worst thing you'll get as an author is radio silence, with no feedback whatsoever. This happens with most stories, be they good, bad, or anywhere in between. Shit happens, and feedback takes work, work that you're - unfortunately - not intrinsically owed. Ironically, if you're new and you're shit, you're actually more likely to get constructive feedback than if you're known (save for a couple of authors who are really loved by the thread). Folks around here are generally fairly mindful of the fact that you're contributing something, and will respond accordingly.

Look at aimbot.exe up above. The dude obviously has some serious issues with English language structure (tenses, clauses, and sentence ordering seem to elude him), and he seems to be bleeding over from the Twokinds thread. All that said, the dude still cranks out content that's fun to read for its own sake. Only shit I remember him getting so far has been for posting furboi in his first story here.

I guess where I'm going with my ramblings is "Just do it! What's the worst that could happen?"

Anonymous Tue 31 Dec 2019 07:46:22 No.27464617 Report
Quoted By:
>>27464356
If you haven't checked out the shared docs someone put in a google drive, search the previous threads for the link.
Don't be discouraged by what you feel. If you read On Writing by Stephen King, he has a veiled moanfest over his own style. He's usually using a simple vocabulary, but sentence builds on sentence. But he trusts his instincts to get out of the way and allow the story to happen.
Take that paragraph. Rewrite it in the other two perspectives versus the original. Have another character watch him. Where is this water? What time of day? Weave in your anxiety; people get out of the water (via bath or shower) everyday, but what made this different?

Ramble for 500 words, and learn. I have 42k words on a work in progress. Guess how many times I've gone in, deleted at least 20% of that, and built back up. One evening I nixed almost 80% of that.
Writing is a puzzle. Sometimes it's a snap, others not.

Anonymous Tue 31 Dec 2019 15:58:39 No.27469630 Report
Quoted By: >>27469774
>>27467138

LOL, sorry man. I didn't mean to say you or your writing was shit. I'd also hate to be the guy to chase any other writers off the general. All that being said, and assuming you're interested in feedback, there is room for improvement in a couple of different aspects of your English fundamentals:

First and foremost, please-oh please, try to maintain a consistent frame for your writing. In all three stories I've read, you bounce between first (I), second (you), and third(he/she) person without a clear perspective change. This is a major no-no in storytelling, barring specific and intentional perspective changes, ones best left to a chapter by chapter or subchapter by subchapter basis.
Maintaining a consistent tense: Your stuff tends to bounce between present and past tense, usually multiple times within the same paragraph. Like with floating story framing, it's not a commentary on your narrative, but is a major no-no in English structure.

An example of when frame changes could work would be a character butting in on the narrator to tell their part of the story. This, however would require a minor breaking of the 4th wall and strict adherence to correct frame for each narrator's section of the story. It would also have to remain written in past tense for both narrators.

All that said, I'm a massive grammar Nazi* and I still powered through, because they've generally been a solid combination of comfy and fappable. Your sense of framing, your story-boarding, and your character writing are all plenty good to write shit that's enjoyable to read. Seriously, honestly, and truly, your best bet to improve rapidly would be to either wait a day before editing, or find someone to edit your stuff.

*Don't mind the myriad spelling errors, run-on sentences, sentence fragments in my posts and/or massive abuse of conjunctive clauses, especially in my posts. These tend to be stream of consciousness and don't get edited.
